# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: substation-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A **circuit breaker** is an electrical safety device designed to protect an electrical circuit from damage caused by current in excess of that which the equipment can safely carry (overcurrent).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Its basic function is to interrupt current flow to protect equipment and to prevent fire.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Unlike a fuse, which interrupts once and then must be replaced, a circuit breaker can be reset (either manually or automatically) to resume normal operation.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are commonly installed in distribution boards.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Apart from its safety purpose, a circuit breaker is also often used as a main switch to manually disconnect ("rack out") and connect ("rack in") electrical power to a whole electrical sub-network.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are made in varying current ratings, from devices that protect low-current circuits or individual household appliances, to switchgear designed to protect high-voltage circuits feeding an entire city.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Any device which protects against excessive current by automatically removing power from a faulty system, such as a circuit breaker or fuse, can be referred to as an *over-current protection device* (*OCPD*).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] An early form of circuit breaker was described by Thomas Edison in an 1879 patent application, although his commercial power distribution system used fuses.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Its purpose was to protect lighting circuit wiring from accidental short circuits and overloads.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A modern miniature circuit breaker similar to the ones now in use was patented by Brown, Boveri & Cie in 1924.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Hugo Stotz, an engineer who had sold his company to Brown, Boveri & Cie, was credited as the inventor on German patent 458392.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Stotz's invention was the forerunner of the modern thermal-magnetic breaker commonly used in household load centers to this day.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Interconnection of multiple generator sources into an electrical grid required the development of circuit breakers with increasing voltage ratings and increased ability to safely interrupt the increasing short-circuit currents produced by networks.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Simple air-break manual switches produced hazardous arcs when interrupting high-voltage circuits; these gave way to oil-enclosed contacts, and various forms using the directed flow of pressurized air, or pressurized oil, to cool and interrupt the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] By 1935, the specially constructed circuit breakers used at the Boulder Dam project used eight series breaks and pressurized oil flow to interrupt faults of up to 2,500 MVA, in three AC cycles.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] All circuit breaker systems have common features in their operation, but details vary substantially depending on the voltage class, current rating and type of the circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker must first detect a fault condition.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In small mains and low-voltage circuit breakers, this is usually done within the device itself.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Typically, the heating or magnetic effects of electric current are employed.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers for large currents or high voltages are usually arranged with protective relay pilot devices to sense a fault condition and to operate the opening mechanism.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These typically require a separate power source, such as a battery, although some high-voltage circuit breakers are self-contained with current transformers, protective relays, and internal power sources.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Once a fault is detected, the circuit breaker contacts must open to interrupt the circuit; this is commonly done using mechanically stored energy contained within the breaker, such as a spring or compressed air to separate the contacts.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A breaker may also use the higher current caused by the fault to separate the contacts, via thermal expansion or increased magnetic field.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A small circuit breaker typically has a manual control lever to switch the circuit off or reset a tripped breaker, while a larger unit may use a solenoid to trip the mechanism, and an electric motor to restore energy to springs (which rapidly separate contacts when the breaker is tripped).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker contacts must carry the load current without excessive heating, and must also withstand the heat of the arc produced when interrupting (opening) the circuit.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Contacts are made of copper or copper alloys, silver alloys and other highly conductive materials.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Service life of the contacts is limited by the erosion of contact material due to arcing while interrupting the current.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Miniature and molded-case circuit breakers are usually discarded when the contacts have worn, but power circuit breakers and high-voltage circuit breakers have replaceable contacts.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] When a high current or voltage is interrupted, an arc is generated.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The maximum length of the arc is generally proportional to the voltage while the intensity (or heat) is proportional to the current.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This arc must be contained, cooled and extinguished in a controlled way, so that the gap between the contacts can again withstand the voltage in the circuit.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Different circuit breakers use vacuum, air, insulating gas, or oil as the medium the arc forms in.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Finally, once the fault condition has been cleared, the contacts must again be closed to restore power to the interrupted circuit.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Low-voltage **miniature circuit breakers** (**MCB**) use air alone to extinguish the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers contain so-called arc chutes, a stack of mutually insulated parallel metal plates that divide and cool the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Splitting the arc into smaller arcs makes the arc cooler as the arc voltage increases and serves as an additional impedance that limits the current through the circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The current-carrying parts near the contacts provide easy deflection of the arc into the arc chutes by a magnetic force of a current path, although magnetic blowout coils or permanent magnets could also deflect the arc into the arc chute (used on circuit breakers for higher ratings).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The number of plates in the arc chute is dependent on the short-circuit rating and nominal voltage of the circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In larger ratings, oil circuit breakers rely upon vaporization of some of the oil to blast a jet of oil through the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Gas (usually sulfur hexafluoride) circuit breakers sometimes stretch the arc using a magnetic field, and then rely upon the dielectric strength of the sulfur hexafluoride (SF6) to quench the stretched arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Vacuum circuit breakers have minimal arcing (as there is nothing to ionize other than the contact material).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The arc is quenched when it is stretched a very small amount (less than 3 mm (0.1 in)).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Vacuum circuit breakers are frequently used in modern medium-voltage switch gear to 38,000 volts.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Air circuit breakers may use compressed air to blow out the arc, or alternatively, the contacts are rapidly swung into a small sealed chamber, the escaping of the displaced air thus blowing out the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are usually able to terminate all current very quickly: typically the arc is extinguished between 30 and 150 ms after the mechanism has been tripped, depending upon age and construction of the device.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The maximum current value and let-through energy determine the quality of the circuit breakers.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are rated both by the normal current that they are expected to carry, and the maximum short-circuit current that they can safely interrupt.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This latter figure is the **ampere interrupting capacity** (**AIC**) of the breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Under short-circuit conditions, the calculated or measured maximum prospective short-circuit current may be many times the normal, rated current of the circuit.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] When electrical contacts open to interrupt a large current, there is a tendency for an arc to form between the opened contacts, which would allow the current to continue.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This condition can create conductive ionized gases and molten or vaporized metal, which can cause the further continuation of the arc or create additional short circuits, potentially resulting in the explosion of the circuit breaker and the equipment that it is installed in.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Therefore, circuit breakers incorporate various features to divide and extinguish the arcs.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The maximum short-circuit current that a breaker can interrupt is determined by testing.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Application of a breaker in a circuit with a prospective short-circuit current higher than the breaker's interrupting capacity rating may result in failure of the breaker to safely interrupt a fault.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In a worst-case scenario, a breaker may successfully interrupt a fault only to explode when reset.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Typical domestic panel circuit breakers are rated to interrupt 10 kA (10,000 A) short-circuit current.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Miniature circuit breakers used to protect control circuits or small appliances may not have sufficient interrupting capacity to use at a panel board; these circuit breakers are called "supplemental circuit protectors" to distinguish them from distribution-type circuit breakers.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are manufactured with standard ratings, using a system of preferred numbers to create a useful selection of ratings.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A miniature circuit breaker has a fixed trip setting; changing the operating current value requires replacing the whole circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers with higher ratings can have adjustable trip settings, allowing fewer standardized products to be used, adjusted to the applicable precise ratings when installed.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] For example, a circuit breaker with a 400 ampere *frame size* might have its over-current detection threshold set only 300 amperes where that rating is appropriate.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] For low-voltage distribution circuit breakers an international standard, IEC 60898-1, defines *rated current* as the maximum current that a breaker is designed to carry continuously.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are also rated by the maximum fault current that they can interrupt; this allows use of more economical devices on systems unlikely to develop the high short-circuit current found on, for example, a large commercial building distribution system.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In the United States, Underwriters Laboratories (UL) certifies equipment ratings, called Series Ratings (or "integrated equipment ratings") for circuit breaker equipment used for buildings.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Power circuit breakers and medium- and high-voltage circuit breakers used for industrial or electric power systems are designed and tested to ANSI or IEEE standards in the C37 series.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] For example, standard C37.16 lists preferred frame size current ratings for power circuit breakers in the range of 600 to 5000 amperes.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Trip current settings and time–current characteristics of these breakers are generally adjustable.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] For medium- and high-voltage circuit breakers used in switchgear, substations and generating stations, relatively few standard frame sizes are generally manufactured.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers are usually controlled by separate protective relay systems, offering adjustable tripping current and time settings as well as allowing for more complex protection schemes.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Many classifications of circuit breakers can be made, based on their features such as voltage class, construction type, interrupting type, and structural features.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The characteristics of low-voltage circuit breakers are given by international standards such as IEC 947.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers are often installed in draw-out enclosures that allow removal and interchange without dismantling the switchgear.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Large low-voltage molded-case and power circuit breakers may have electric motor operators so they can open and close under remote control.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These may form part of an automatic transfer switch system for standby power.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Low-voltage circuit breakers are also made for direct-current (DC) applications, such as for subway lines.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Direct current requires special breakers because the arc is continuous—unlike an AC arc, which tends to go out on each half cycle, a direct-current circuit breaker has a blow-out coil that generates a magnetic field that rapidly stretches the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Small circuit breakers are either installed directly in equipment or arranged in breaker panels.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The DIN-rail-mounted thermal-magnetic miniature circuit breaker is the most common style in modern domestic consumer units and commercial electrical distribution boards throughout Europe.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Actuator mechanism – forces the contacts together or apart.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Contacts – allow current when touching and break the current when moved apart.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Calibration screw – allows the manufacturer to precisely adjust the trip current of the device after assembly.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A *magnetic* circuit breaker uses a solenoid (electromagnet) whose pulling force increases with the current.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Certain designs utilize electromagnetic forces in addition to those of the solenoid.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker contacts are held closed by a latch.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] As the current in the solenoid increases beyond the rating of the circuit breaker, the solenoid's pull releases the latch, which lets the contacts open by spring action.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] They are the most commonly used circuit breakers in the United States.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The thermal portion of the circuit breaker provides a time-response feature that trips the circuit breaker sooner for larger over-currents but allows smaller overloads to persist for a longer time.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This allows short current spikes such as are produced when a motor or other non-resistive load is switched on.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] With a very large over-current, such as may be caused short circuit, the magnetic element trips the circuit breaker with no intentional additional delay.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A *magnetic–hydraulic* circuit breaker uses a solenoid coil to provide operating force to open the contacts.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A magnetic–hydraulic breaker incorporates a hydraulic time delay feature using a viscous fluid.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A spring restrains the core until the current exceeds the breaker rating.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] During an overload, the speed of the solenoid motion is restricted by the fluid.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The delay permits brief current surges beyond normal running current for motor starting, energizing equipment, etc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Short-circuit currents provide sufficient solenoid force to release the latch regardless of core position thus bypassing the delay feature.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Ambient temperature affects the time delay but does not affect the current rating of a magnetic breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A large power circuit breaker, such as one applied in circuits of more than 1000 volts, may incorporate hydraulic elements in the contact operating mechanism.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Hydraulic energy may be supplied by a pump or stored in accumulators.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These form a distinct type from oil-filled circuit breakers where oil is the arc-extinguishing medium.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] To provide simultaneous breaking on multiple circuits from a fault on any one, circuit breakers may be made as a ganged assembly.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This is a very common requirement for three-phase systems, where breaking may be either three- or four-pole (solid or switched neutral).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Some makers make ganging kits to allow groups of single-phase breakers to be interlinked as required.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In the US, where split-phase supplies are common, in a branch circuit with more than one live conductor, each live conductor must be protected by a breaker pole.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] To ensure that all live conductors are interrupted when any pole trips, a *common-trip* set of breakers must be used.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These may either contain two or three tripping mechanisms within one case or, for small breakers, have the breakers externally tied together via their operating handles.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Two-pole common-trip breakers are common on 120/240-volt systems where 240 volt loads (including major appliances or further distribution boards) span the two live wires.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Three-pole common-trip breakers are typically used to supply three-phase power to powerful motors or further distribution boards.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This is why only common-trip breakers must be used when neutral wire switching is needed.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These are often used to cut the power when a high-risk event occurs, such as a fire or flood alarm, or another electrical condition, such as over-voltage detection.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Shunt trips may be a user-fitted accessory to a standard breaker or supplied as an integral part of a circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers rated between 1 and 72 kV may be assembled into metal-enclosed switchgear line-ups for indoor use or may be individual components installed outdoors in a substation.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Air-break circuit breakers replaced oil-filled units for indoor applications, but are now themselves being replaced by vacuum circuit breakers (up to about 40.5 kV).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Like the high-voltage circuit breakers described below, these are also operated by current-sensing protective relays operated through current transformers.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The characteristics of MV breakers are given by international standards such as IEC 62271.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers nearly always use separate current sensors and protective relays instead of relying on built-in thermal or magnetic overcurrent sensors.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers may be connected into the circuit by bolted connections to bus bars or wires, especially in outdoor switchyards.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers in switchgear line-ups are often built with draw-out construction, allowing breaker removal without disturbing power circuit connections, using a motor-operated or hand-cranked mechanism to separate the breaker from its enclosure.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Electrical power transmission networks are protected and controlled by high-voltage breakers.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The definition of *high voltage* varies but in power transmission work is usually thought to be 72.5 kV or higher, according to a recent definition by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] High-voltage breakers are nearly always solenoid-operated, with current sensing protective relays operated through current transformers.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In substations the protective relay scheme can be complex, protecting equipment and buses from various types of overload or ground/earth fault.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Due to environmental and cost concerns over insulating oil spills, most new breakers use SF6 gas to quench the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers can be classified as *live tank*, where the enclosure that contains the breaking mechanism is at line potential, or *dead tank* with the enclosure at earth potential.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] High-voltage AC circuit breakers are routinely available with ratings up to 765 kV.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] 1,200 kV breakers were launched by Siemens in November 2011, followed by ABB in April the following year.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] High-voltage circuit breakers used on transmission systems may be arranged to allow a single pole of a three-phase line to trip, instead of tripping all three poles; for some classes of faults this improves the system stability and availability.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] High-voltage direct current circuit breakers are still a field of research as of 2015.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Such breakers would be useful to interconnect HVDC transmission systems.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A sulfur hexafluoride circuit breaker uses contacts surrounded by sulfur hexafluoride gas to quench the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] They are most often used for transmission-level voltages and may be incorporated into compact gas-insulated switchgear.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In cold climates, supplemental heating or different gas mixtures are used for high voltage circuit breakers, due to liquefaction of the SF6 gas.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In some northern power grids, gas mixtures of N2 and SF6, or CF4 and SF6 are installed in puffer-type HVCB to quench the arc without any liquefaction of the gas.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The minimum temperature ratings of these models are as low as -50 °C for some northern substations.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The disconnecting circuit breaker (DCB) was introduced in 2000 and is a high-voltage circuit breaker modeled after the SF6-breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] It presents a technical solution where the disconnecting function is integrated in the breaking chamber, eliminating the need for separate disconnectors.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This increases the availability, since open-air disconnecting switch main contacts need maintenance every 2–6 years, while modern circuit breakers have maintenance intervals of 15 years.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Implementing a DCB solution also reduces the space requirements within the substation, and increases the reliability, due to the lack of separate disconnectors.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In order to further reduce the required space of substation, as well as simplifying the design and engineering of the substation, a fiber optic current sensor (FOCS) can be integrated with the DCB.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A 420 kV DCB with integrated FOCS can reduce a substation's footprint with over 50% compared to a conventional solution of live tank breakers with disconnectors and current transformers, due to reduced material and no additional insulation medium.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In 2012, ABB presented a 75 kV high-voltage breaker that uses carbon dioxide as the medium to extinguish the arc.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The carbon dioxide breaker works on the same principles as an SF6 breaker and can also be produced as a disconnecting circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] By switching from SF6 to CO2, it is possible to reduce the CO2 emissions by 10 tons during the product's life cycle.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] A smart circuit breaker is an electronic overcurrent protection device that integrates high-frequency sensors and Internet-of-Things (IoT) connectivity to provide intelligent control and real-time monitoring of electrical circuits.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Unlike traditional circuit breakers, smart breakers utilize digital logic and communication to augment their operation.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Protocols such as Wi-Fi, Zigbee, or cellular networks are used to gather and transmit granular electrical data including voltage, current, and power quality .
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] These devices are implemented either as modular components that replace standard breakers in a compatible load center or as core elements of a comprehensive smart electrical panel.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] This technology transforms the breaker box into an active "energy hub," often capable of decision-making and precise circuit-level metering.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] One of the primary use case for smart circuit breakers in residential environments is the optimization of home energy management systems (HEMS), especially those incorporating solar arrays, electric vehicle (EV) chargers, and battery storage .
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Through mobile applications, users can remotely actuate circuits, schedule high-intensity loads to run during off-peak hours for cost savings, and implement dynamic load shedding to prioritize essential appliances during power outages.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] Using these can provide significant benefits in reducing battery cycling and increasing the power capacity of existing electrical service .
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] In commercial and industrial settings, smart breakers are integrated with Building Management Systems (BMS) to enable advanced functions such as automated tenant billing, demand response participation, and predictive maintenance through anomaly detection.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] By intelligently managing demand, these systems allow facilities to scale energy-intensive infrastructure without necessitating costly utility service upgrades.
[src:substation-automation/circuit-breaker] The following types are described in separate articles.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A **substation** is a part of an electrical generation, transmission, and distribution system.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations transform voltage from high to low, or the reverse, or perform any of several other important functions.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Between the generating station and the consumer, electric power may flow through several substations at different voltage levels.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A substation may include transformers to change voltage levels between high transmission voltages and lower distribution voltages, or at the interconnection of two different transmission voltages.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] They are a common component of the infrastructure.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] As of 2002, there were approximately 55,000 substations in the United States.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations are also occasionally known in some countries as **switchyards**.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations may be owned and operated by an electrical utility, or may be owned by a large industrial or commercial customer.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Generally substations are unattended, relying on SCADA for remote supervision and control.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The word *substation* comes from the days before the distribution system became a grid.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] As central generation stations became larger, smaller generating plants were converted to distribution stations, receiving their energy supply from a larger plant instead of using their own generators.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The first substations were connected to only one power station, where the generators were housed, and were subsidiaries of that power station.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations may be designed and built by a contractor or alternately all phases of its development may be handled by the electrical utility.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Most commonly, the utility does the engineering and procurement while hiring a contractor for actual construction.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Major design constraints for construction of substations include land availability and cost, limitations on the construction period, transportation restrictions, and the need to get the substation running quickly.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Prefabrication is a common way to reduce the construction cost.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] For connecting the new substation, a partial outage at another substation may be required, but the utility often tries to minimize downtime.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A *transmission substation* connects two or more transmission lines.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The simplest case is where all transmission lines have the same voltage.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In such cases, substation contains high-voltage switches that allow lines to be connected or isolated for fault clearance or maintenance.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Transmission substations can range from simple to complex.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A small "switching station" may be little more than a bus plus some circuit breakers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The largest transmission substations can cover a large area (several acres/hectares) with multiple voltage levels, many circuit breakers, and a large amount of protection and control equipment (voltage and current transformers, relays and SCADA systems).
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Modern substations may be implemented using international standards such as IEC Standard 61850.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A *distribution substation* transfers power from the transmission system to the distribution system of an area.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] It is uneconomical to directly connect electricity consumers to the main transmission network, unless they use large amounts of power, so the distribution station reduces voltage to a level suitable for local distribution.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The input for a distribution substation is typically at least two transmission or sub-transmission lines.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Input voltage may be, for example, 115 kV, or whatever is common in the area.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Distribution voltages are typically medium voltage, between 2.4 kV and 33 kV, depending on the size of the area served and the practices of the local utility.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The feeders run along streets overhead (or underground, in some cases) and power the distribution transformers at or near the customer premises.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In addition to transforming voltage, distribution substations also isolate faults in either the transmission or distribution systems.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Distribution substations are typically the points of voltage regulation, although on long distribution circuits (of several miles/kilometers), voltage regulation equipment may also be installed along the line.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The downtown areas of large cities feature complicated distribution substations, with high-voltage switching, and switching and backup systems on the low-voltage side.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] More typical distribution substations have a switch, one transformer, and minimal facilities on the low-voltage side.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In distributed generation projects such as a wind farm or photovoltaic power station, a collector substation may be required.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] It resembles a distribution substation although power flow is in the opposite direction, from many wind turbines or inverters up into the transmission grid.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Usually for economy of construction the collector system operates around 35 kV, although some collector systems are 12 kV, and the collector substation steps up voltage to a transmission voltage for the grid.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The collector substation can also provide power factor correction if it is needed, metering, and control of the wind farm.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In some special cases a collector substation can also contain an HVDC converter station.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Collector substations also exist where multiple thermal or hydroelectric power plants of comparable output power are in proximity.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Examples for such substations are Brauweiler in Germany and Hradec in the Czech Republic, where power is collected from nearby lignite-fired power plants.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] If no transformers are required for increasing the voltage to transmission level, the substation is a switching station.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Converter substations may be associated with HVDC converter plants, traction current, or interconnected non-synchronous networks.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] These stations contain power electronic devices to change the frequency of current, or else convert from alternating to direct current or the reverse.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Formerly rotary converters changed frequency to interconnect two systems; nowadays such substations are rare.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A switching station is a substation without transformers and operating only at a single voltage level.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Switching stations are sometimes used as collector and distribution stations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are used for switching the current to back-up lines or for parallelizing circuits in case of failure.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] An example is the switching stations for the Inga–Shaba HVDC transmission line.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A switching station may also be known as a switchyard, and these are commonly located directly adjacent to or nearby a power station.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In this case the generators from the power station supply their power into the yard onto the generator bus on one side of the yard, and the transmission lines take their power from a Feeder Bus on the other side of the yard.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] An important function performed by a substation is switching, which is the connecting and disconnecting of transmission lines or other components to and from the system.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Switching events may be planned or unplanned.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A transmission line or other component may need to be de-energized for maintenance or for new construction, for example, adding or removing a transmission line or a transformer.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] To maintain reliability of supply, companies aim at keeping the system up and running while performing maintenance.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] All work to be performed, from routine testing to adding entirely new substations, should be done while keeping the whole system running.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The function of the switching station is to isolate the faulty portion of the system in the shortest possible time.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] De-energizing faulty equipment protects it from further damage, and isolating a fault helps keep the rest of the electrical grid operating with stability.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Electrified railways also use substations, often distribution substations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In some cases a conversion of the current type takes place, commonly with rectifiers for direct current (DC) trains, or rotary converters for trains using alternating current (AC) at frequencies other than that of the public grid.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are also transmission substations or collector substations if the railway network also operates its own grid and generators to supply the other stations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A *mobile substation* is a substation on wheels, containing a transformer, breakers and buswork mounted on a self-contained semi-trailer, meant to be pulled by a truck.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] They are designed to be compact for travel on public roads, and are used for temporary backup in times of natural disaster or war.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Mobile substations are usually rated much lower than permanent installations, and may be built in several units to meet road travel limitations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substation design is aimed at minimizing cost while ensuring power availability and reliability, and enabling changes to the substation in the future.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations may be built outdoors, indoors, or underground or in a combination of these locations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Selection of the location of a substation must consider many factors.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Sufficient land area is required for installation of equipment with necessary clearances for electrical safety, and for access to maintain large apparatus such as transformers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The site must have room for expansion due to load growth or planned transmission additions.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Environmental effects of the substation must be considered, such as drainage, noise and road traffic effects.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The substation site must be reasonably central to the distribution area to be served.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The site must be secure from intrusion by passers-by, both to protect people from injury by electric shock or arcs, and to protect the electrical system from misoperation due to vandalism.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] If not owned and operated by a utility company, substations are typically occupied on a long lease such as a renewable 99-year lease, giving the utility company security of tenure.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The first step in planning a substation layout is the preparation of a single-line diagram, which shows in simplified form the switching and protection arrangement required, as well as the incoming supply lines and outgoing feeders or transmission lines.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] It is a usual practice by many electrical utilities to prepare one-line diagrams with principal elements (lines, switches, circuit breakers, transformers) arranged on the page similarly to the way the apparatus would be laid out in the actual station.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In a common design, incoming lines have a disconnector and a circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In some cases, the lines will not have both, with either a switch or a circuit breaker being all that is considered necessary.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A disconnect switch is used to provide isolation, since it cannot interrupt load current.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A circuit breaker is used as a protection device to interrupt fault currents automatically, and may be used to switch loads on and off, or to cut off a line when power is flowing in the 'wrong' direction.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] When a large fault current flows through the circuit breaker, this is detected through the use of current transformers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The magnitude of the current transformer outputs may be used to trip the circuit breaker resulting in a disconnection of the load supplied by the circuit break from the feeding point.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] This seeks to isolate the fault point from the rest of the system, and allow the rest of the system to continue operating with minimal impact.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Both switches and circuit breakers may be operated locally (within the substation) or remotely from a supervisory control center.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] With overhead transmission lines, the propagation of lightning and switching surges can cause insulation failures into substation equipment.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Line entrance surge arrestors are used to protect substation equipment accordingly.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Insulation Coordination studies are carried out extensively to ensure equipment failure (and associated outages) is minimal.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Once past the switching components, the lines of a given voltage connect to one or more buses.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] These are sets of busbars, usually in multiples of three, since three-phase electrical power distribution is largely universal around the world.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The arrangement of switches, circuit breakers, and buses used affects the cost and reliability of the substation.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] For important substations a ring bus, double bus, or so-called "breaker and a half" setup can be used, so that the failure of any one circuit breaker does not interrupt power to other circuits, and so that parts of the substation may be de-energized for maintenance and repairs.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations feeding only a single industrial load may have minimal switching provisions, especially for small installations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Because of the risk of electrical shock, substations are inherently dangerous to electrical workers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] To mitigate this hazard, substations are designed with various safety features.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Live conductors and bare equipment are kept separate, either with protected equipment, or using screens or distance.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] To this is added the necessary space for employees to work safely and vehicles to pass.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Sometimes it is necessary to work on parts of the substation while energized, but employees must maintain a safe distance of at least 3 metres (9.8 ft).
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The aim to reduce substation footprints comes into conflict with ease of maintenance enhanced by including gaps where employees can safely work.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Underneath a substation, a mat or grid of conductors laid around 0.5 or 0.6 metres (1 ft 8 in or 2 ft 0 in) underground provides grounding.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] This grid, which is typically copper although it may be galvanized iron in some countries, is used to ground circuits that are being worked on to prevent accidental re-energization while workers are in contact with a de-energized circuit.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Often, earth rods are driven deeper into the ground from the grounding grid for lower resistance grounding, and may be surrounded by bentonite or marconite to further reduce resistance and ensure effective grounding for the lifetime of the substation.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Above ground, the grounding conductors may be steel, aluminum, or copper.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] They must be thick enough to carry the expected current of a fault for 1–3 seconds and remain undamaged.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substation fences, typically at least 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in height, both protect the public from electrical hazards and also protect the substation from vandalism.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Internal fences can also be incorporated to protect employees from areas that are unsafe when energized.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations generally have switching, protection and control equipment, and transformers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] In a large substation, circuit breakers are used to interrupt any short circuits or overload currents that may occur on the network.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Smaller distribution stations may use recloser circuit breakers or fuses for protection of distribution circuits.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations themselves do not usually have generators, although a power plant may have a substation nearby.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Other devices such as capacitors, voltage regulators, and reactors may also be located at a substation.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations may be on the surface in fenced enclosures, underground, or special-purpose buildings.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] High-rise buildings may have several indoor substations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Indoor substations are usually found in urban areas to reduce the noise from transformers, improve appearance, or protect switchgear from extreme climate or pollution.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Substations often use busbars as conductors between electrical equipment.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Busbars may be aluminum tubing 3–6 inches (76–152 mm) thick, or else wires (strain bus).
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Outdoor, above-ground substation structures include wood pole, lattice metal tower, and tubular metal structures, although other variants are available.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Where space is plentiful and appearance of the station is not a factor, steel lattice towers provide low-cost supports for transmission lines and apparatus.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Low-profile substations may be specified in suburban areas where appearance is more critical.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Indoor substations may be gas insulated substations (GIS) (at high voltages, with gas insulated switchgear), or use metal-enclosed or metal-clad switchgear at lower voltages.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Urban and suburban indoor substations may be finished on the outside so as to blend in with other buildings in the area.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] A *compact substation* is generally an outdoor substation built in a metal enclosure, in which each item of the electrical equipment is located very near to each other to create a relatively smaller footprint size of the substation.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] High-voltage circuit breakers are commonly used to interrupt the flow of current in substation equipment.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] At the time of interruption, current could be normal, too high due to excessive load, unusual due to a fault, or tripped by protective relays prior to anticipated trouble.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Reclosers are similar to breakers, and can be cheaper because they do not require separate protective relays.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Often used in distribution, they often are programmed to trip when the amps exceed a certain amount over a period of time.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Reclosers will attempt to re-energize the circuit after a delay.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] If unsuccessful for a few times, the recloser will have to be manually reset by an electrical worker.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Capacitor banks are used in substations to balance the lagging current draw from inductive loads (such as motors, transformers, and some industrial equipment) with their reactive load.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Additional capacitor capacity may be needed if dispersed generation (such as small diesel generators, rooftop photovoltaic solar panels, or wind turbines) are added to the system.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Capacitors can reduce the current in wires, helping stem system losses from voltage drop or enabling extra power to be sent through the conductors.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Capacitors may be left on in response to constant inductive load or turned on when inductive load is increased, such as in the summer for air conditioners.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The switching may be remote and can be done manually or automatically.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Larger substations have control rooms for the equipment used to monitor, control, and protect the rest of the substation equipment.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] It often contains protective relays, meters, breaker controls, communications, batteries, and recorders that save detailed data about substation operations, particularly when there is any unusual activity, to help reconstruct what happened after the fact.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] These control rooms typically are heated and air conditioned to ensure the reliable operation of this equipment.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Additional equipment is necessary to handle power surges associated with intermittent renewable energy such as dispersed generation from wind or solar.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Most transformers lose between 5 and 1.5 percent of their input as heat and noise.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Iron losses are no-load and constant whenever the transformer is energized, while copper and auxiliary losses are proportionate to the square of the current.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Auxiliary losses are due to running fans and pumps which is noisy when the transformer is operating at maximum capacity.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] To reduce noise, enclosures are often built around the transformer and can also be added after the substation is built.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Oil-based transformers are often built with bunded areas to prevent the escape of flaming or leaking oil.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Fire separation areas or firewalls are built around the transformer to stop the spread of fire.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Firefighting vehicles are allowed a path to access the area.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Maintenance of substations involves inspections, data collection and analysis, and routine scheduled work.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Using methods such as infrared scanning and dissolved gas analysis, it can be predicted when the substation will need maintenance and predict dangers before they materialize.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Infrared technology finds hot spots in the substation where electrical energy is being converted to heat, which indicates a problem and can cause additional damage from the high heat.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Dissolved gas analysis can tell when an oil-insulated transformer needs to have the oil filtered or replaced, and also detect other issues.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Early electrical substations required manual switching or adjustment of equipment, and manual collection of data for load, energy consumption, and abnormal events.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] As the complexity of distribution networks grew, it became economically necessary to automate supervision and control of substations from a centrally attended point, to allow overall coordination in case of emergencies and to reduce operating costs.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Early efforts to remote control substations used dedicated communication wires, often run alongside power circuits.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Power-line carrier, microwave radio, fiber optic cables as well as dedicated wired remote control circuits have all been applied to Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) for substations.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] The development of the microprocessor made for an exponential increase in the number of points that could be economically controlled and monitored.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Today, standardized communication protocols such as DNP3, IEC 61850 and Modbus, to list a few, are used to allow multiple intelligent electronic devices to communicate with each other and supervisory control centers.
[src:substation-automation/electrical-substation] Distributed automatic control at substations is one element of the so-called smart grid.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] In the electric power industry, an **intelligent electronic device** (**IED**) is an integrated microprocessor-based controller of power system equipment, such as circuit breakers, transformers and capacitor banks.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] IEDs receive data from sensors and power equipment and can issue control commands, such as tripping circuit breakers if they sense voltage, current, or frequency anomalies, or raise/lower tap positions in order to maintain the desired voltage level.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Common types of IEDs include protective relaying devices, tap changer controllers, circuit breaker controllers, capacitor bank switches, recloser controllers, voltage regulators etc.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] This is generally controlled by a setting file.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] The testing of setting files is typically one of the most time-consuming roles of a protection tester.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Digital protective relays are primarily IEDs, using a microprocessor to perform several protective, control and similar functions.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Some recent IEDs are designed to support the IEC61850 standard for substation automation, which provides interoperability and advanced communications capabilities.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] IEDs are used as a more modern alternative to, or a complement of, setup with traditional remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Unlike the RTUs, IEDs are integrated with the devices they control and offer a standardized set of measuring and control points that is easier to configure and require less wiring.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Most IEDs have a communication port and built-in support for standard communication protocols (DNP3, IEC104 or IEC 61850), so they can communicate directly with the SCADA system or a substation programmable logic controller.
[src:substation-automation/intelligent-electronic-device] Alternatively, they can be connected to a substation RTU that acts as a gateway towards the SCADA server.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In electrical engineering, a **protective relay** is a relay device designed to trip a circuit breaker when a fault is detected.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The first protective relays were electromagnetic devices, relying on coils operating on moving parts to provide detection of abnormal operating conditions such as over-current, overvoltage, reverse power flow, over-frequency, and under-frequency.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Microprocessor-based solid-state digital protection relays now emulate the original devices, as well as providing types of protection and supervision impractical with electromechanical relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Electromechanical relays provide only rudimentary indication of the location and origin of a fault.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In many cases a single microprocessor relay provides functions that would take two or more electromechanical devices.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] By combining several functions in one case, numerical relays also save capital cost and maintenance cost over electromechanical relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] However, due to their very long life span, tens of thousands of these "silent sentinels" are still protecting transmission lines and electrical apparatus all over the world.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Important transmission lines and generators have cubicles dedicated to protection, with many individual electromechanical devices, or one or two microprocessor relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The theory and application of these protective devices is an important part of the education of a power engineer who specializes in power system protection.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The need to act quickly to protect circuits and equipment often requires protective relays to respond and trip a breaker within a few thousandths of a second.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In some instances these clearance times are prescribed in legislation or operating rules.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A maintenance or testing program is used to determine the performance and availability of protection systems.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Based on the end application and applicable legislation, various standards such as ANSI C37.90, IEC255-4, IEC60255-3, and IAC govern the response time of the relay to the fault conditions that may occur.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Electromechanical protective relays operate by either magnetic attraction, or magnetic induction.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Unlike switching type electromechanical relays with fixed and usually ill-defined operating voltage thresholds and operating times, protective relays have well-established, selectable, and adjustable time and current (or other operating parameter) operating characteristics.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Protection relays may use arrays of induction disks, shaded-pole, magnets, operating and restraint coils, solenoid-type operators, telephone-relay contacts, and phase-shifting networks.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Protective relays can also be classified by the type of measurement they make.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A protective relay may respond to the magnitude of a quantity such as voltage or current.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Induction relays can respond to the product of two quantities in two field coils, which could for example represent the power in a circuit.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "It is not practical to make a relay that develops a torque equal to the quotient of two a.c. quantities.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Several operating coils can be used to provide "bias" to the relay, allowing the sensitivity of response in one circuit to be controlled by another.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Various combinations of "operate torque" and "restraint torque" can be produced in the relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] By use of a permanent magnet in the magnetic circuit, a relay can be made to respond to current in one direction differently from in another.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Such polarized relays are used on direct-current circuits to detect, for example, reverse current into a generator.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] These relays can be made bistable, maintaining a contact closed with no coil current and requiring reverse current to reset.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] For AC circuits, the principle is extended with a polarizing winding connected to a reference voltage source.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Lightweight contacts make for sensitive relays that operate quickly, but small contacts can't carry or break heavy currents.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Often the measuring relay will trigger auxiliary telephone-type armature relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In a large installation of electromechanical relays, it would be difficult to determine which device originated the signal that tripped the circuit.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] This information is useful to operating personnel to determine the likely cause of the fault and to prevent its re-occurrence.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Relays may be fitted with a "target" or "flag" unit, which is released when the relay operates, to display a distinctive colored signal when the relay has tripped.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "Armature"-type relays have a pivoted lever supported on a hinge or knife-edge pivot, which carries a moving contact.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] These relays may work on either alternating or direct current, but for alternating current, a shading coil on the pole is used to maintain contact force throughout the alternating current cycle.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Because the air gap between the fixed coil and the moving armature becomes much smaller when the relay has operated, the current required to maintain the relay closed is much smaller than the current to first operate it.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The "returning ratio" or "differential" is the measure of how much the current must be reduced to reset the relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A variant application of the attraction principle is the plunger-type or solenoid operator.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A reed relay is another example of the attraction principle.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "Moving coil" meters use a loop of wire turns in a stationary magnet, similar to a galvanometer but with a contact lever instead of a pointer.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] These can be made with very high sensitivity.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Another type of moving coil suspends the coil from two conductive ligaments, allowing very long travel of the coil.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "Induction" disk meters work by inducing currents in a disk that is free to rotate; the rotary motion of the disk operates a contact.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Induction relays require alternating current; if two or more coils are used, they must be at the same frequency otherwise no net operating force is produced.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] These electromagnetic relays use the induction principle discovered by Galileo Ferraris in the late 19th century.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The magnetic system in induction disc overcurrent relays is designed to detect overcurrents in a power system and operate with a pre-determined time delay when certain overcurrent limits have been reached.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The following important conclusions can be drawn from the above equation.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The relay's primary winding is supplied from the power systems current transformer via a plug bridge, which is called the plug setting multiplier (psm).
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Usually seven equally spaced tappings or operating bands determine the relays sensitivity.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The primary winding is located on the upper electromagnet.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The secondary winding has connections on the upper electromagnet that are energised from the primary winding and connected to the lower electromagnet.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Once the upper and lower electromagnets are energised they produce eddy currents that are induced onto the metal disc and flow through the flux paths.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] This relationship of eddy currents and fluxes creates torque proportional to the input current of the primary winding, due to the two flux paths being out of phase by 90°.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In an overcurrent condition, a value of current will be reached that overcomes the control spring pressure on the spindle and the braking magnet, causing the metal disc to rotate towards the fixed contact.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] This initial movement of the disc is also held off to a critical positive value of current by small slots that are often cut into the side of the disc.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The time taken for rotation to make the contacts is not only dependent on current but also the spindle backstop position, known as the time multiplier (tm).
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The time multiplier is divided into 10 linear divisions of the full rotation time.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Providing the relay is free from dirt, the metal disc and the spindle with its contact will reach the fixed contact, thus sending a signal to trip and isolate the circuit, within its designed time and current specifications.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Drop off current of the relay is much lower than its operating value, and once reached the relay will be reset in a reverse motion by the pressure of the control spring governed by the braking magnet.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Application of electronic amplifiers to protective relays was described as early as 1928, using vacuum tube amplifiers and continued up to 1956.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Devices using electron tubes were studied but never applied as commercial products, because of the limitations of vacuum tube amplifiers.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A relatively large standby current is required to maintain the tube filament temperature; inconvenient high voltages are required for the circuits, and vacuum tube amplifiers had difficulty with incorrect operation due to noise disturbances.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Static relays have no or few moving parts, and became practical with the introduction of the transistor.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Measuring elements of static relays have been successfully and economically built up from diodes, zener diodes, avalanche diodes, unijunction transistors, p-n-p and n-p-n bipolar transistors, field effect transistors or their combinations.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Static relays offer the advantage of higher sensitivity than purely electromechanical relays, because power to operate output contacts is derived from a separate supply, not from the signal circuits.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Static relays eliminated or reduced contact bounce, and could provide fast operation, long life and low maintenance.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Digital protective relays were in their infancy during the late 1960s.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] An experimental digital protection system was tested in the lab and in the field in the early 1970s.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Unlike the relays mentioned above, digital protective relays have two main parts: hardware and software.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The world's first commercially available digital protective relay was introduced to the power industry in 1984 by Schweitzer Engineering Laboratories (SEL) based in Pullman, Washington.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In spite of the developments of complex algorithms for implementing protection functions the microprocessor based-relays marketed in the 1980s did not incorporate them.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A microprocessor-based digital protection relay can replace the functions of many discrete electromechanical instruments.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] These relays convert voltage and currents to digital form and process the resulting measurements using a microprocessor.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The digital relay can emulate functions of many discrete electromechanical relays in one device, simplifying protection design and maintenance.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Each digital relay can run self-test routines to confirm its readiness and alarm if a fault is detected.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Digital relays can also provide functions such as communications (SCADA) interface, monitoring of contact inputs, metering, waveform analysis, and other useful features.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Digital relays can, for example, store multiple sets of protection parameters, which allows the behavior of the relay to be changed during maintenance of attached equipment.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Digital relays also can provide protection strategies impossible to implement with electromechanical relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] This is particularly so in long-distance high voltage or multi-terminal circuits or in lines that are series or shunt compensated They also offer benefits in self-testing and communication to supervisory control systems.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The distinction between digital and numerical protection relay rests on points of fine technical detail, and is rarely found in areas other than Protection.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Numerical relays are the product of the advances in technology from digital relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Generally, there are several different types of numerical protection relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Each type, however, shares a similar architecture, thus enabling designers to build an entire system solution that is based on a relatively small number of flexible components.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] They use high speed processors executing appropriate algorithms.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Most numerical relays are also multifunctional and have multiple setting groups each often with tens or hundreds of settings.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The various protective functions available on a given relay are denoted by standard ANSI device numbers.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] For example, a relay including function 51 would be a timed overcurrent protective relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] An **overcurrent relay** is a type of protective relay which operates when the load current exceeds a pickup value.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] It is of two types: instantaneous over current (IOC) relay and definite time overcurrent (DTOC) relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The ANSI device number is 50 for an IOC relay or a DTOC relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] In a typical application, the over current relay is connected to a current transformer and calibrated to operate at or above a specific current level.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] When the relay operates, one or more contacts will operate and energize to trip a circuit breaker.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The DTOC relay has been used extensively in the United Kingdom but its inherent issue of operating slower for faults closer to the source led to the development of the IDMT relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A **definite time over-current (DTOC) relay** is a relay that operates after a definite period of time once the current exceeds the pickup value.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Hence, this relay has current setting range as well as time setting range.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] An **instantaneous over-current relay** is an overcurrent relay which has no intentional time delay for operation.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The contacts of the relay are closed instantly when the current inside the relay rises beyond the operational value.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The time interval between the instant pick-up value and the closing contacts of the relay is very low.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] It has low operating time and starts operating instantly when the value of current is more than the relay setting.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] This relay operates only when the impedance between the source and the relay is less than that provided in the section.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] An **inverse-time over-current (ITOC) relay** is an overcurrent relay which operates only when the magnitude of their operating current is inversely proportional to the magnitude of the energize quantities.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The operating time of relay decreases with the increases in the current.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The operation of the relay depends on the magnitude of the current.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] An **inverse definite minimum time (IDMT) relay** is a protective relay which is developed to overcome the shortcomings of the definite time overcurrent (DTOC) relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] If the source impedance remains constant and the fault current changes appreciably as we move away from the relay then it is advantageous to use IDMT overcurrent protection to achieve high speed protection over a large section of the protected circuit.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] However, if the source impedance is significantly larger than the feeder impedance then the characteristic of the IDMT relay cannot be exploited and DTOC may be utilized.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Secondly if the source impedance varies and becomes weaker with less generation during light loads then this leads to slower clearance time hence negating the purpose of the IDMT relay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] IEC standard 60255-151 specifies the IDMT relay curves as shown below.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The four curves in Table 1 are derived from the now withdrawn British Standard BS 142.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The other five, in Table 2, are derived from the ANSI standard C37.112.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] While it is more common to use IDMT relays for current protection it is possible to utilize IDMT mode of operation for voltage protection.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] It is possible to program customised curves in some protective relays and other manufacturers have special curves specific to their relays.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Some numerical relays can be used to provide inverse time overvoltage protection or negative sequence overcurrent protection.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Ir = is the ratio of the fault current to the relay setting current or a Plug Setting Multiplier.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "Plug" is a reference from the electromechanical relay era and were available in discrete steps.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The above equations result in a "family" of curves as a result of using different time multiplier setting (TMS) settings.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] It is evident from the relay characteristic equations that a larger TMS will result in a slower clearance time for a given PMS (Ir) value.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A differential scheme acts on the difference between current entering a protected zone (which may be a bus bar, generator, transformer or other apparatus) and the current leaving that zone.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A fault outside the zone gives the same fault current at the entry and exit of the zone, but faults within the zone show up as a difference in current.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] "The differential protection is 100% selective and therefore only responds to faults within its protected zone.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The boundary of the protected zone is uniquely defined by the location of the current transformers.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Time grading with other protection systems is therefore not required, allowing for tripping without additional delay.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Differential protection can be used to provide protection for zones with multiple terminals and can be used to protect lines, generators, motors, transformers, and other electrical plant.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A **directional relay** uses an additional polarizing source of voltage or current to determine the direction of a fault.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Directional elements respond to the phase shift between a polarizing quantity and an operate quantity.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] The fault can be located upstream or downstream of the relay's location, allowing appropriate protective devices to be operated inside or outside of the zone of protection.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A synchronism checking relay provides a contact closure when the frequency and phase of two sources are similar to within some tolerance margin.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] A "synch check" relay is often applied where two power systems are interconnected, such as at a switchyard connecting two power grids, or at a generator circuit breaker to ensure the generator is synchronized to the system before connecting it.
[src:substation-automation/protective-relay] Relays can also be classified by their type of power source.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Other terms that may be used for RTU are **remote telemetry unit** and **remote telecontrol unit**.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU monitors the field digital and analog parameters and transmits data to a SCADA Master Station.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] It runs setup software to connect data input streams to data output streams, define communication protocols, and troubleshoot installation problems in the field.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU might even be a small process control unit with a small database for PID, Alarming, Filtering, Trending and other functions complemented with some BASIC (programming language) tasks.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs typically support the IEC 61131-3 programming standard for programmable logic controllers.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] For example, it communicates via RS485 or wireless communication links in a multi-drop configuration.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] In this type of configuration it is a remote unit that collects data and performs simple control tasks.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] It does not have moving parts and uses extremely low power and is often solar powered.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] A form of power supply will be included for operation from the AC mains for various CPU, status wetting voltages and other interface cards.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] This may consist of AC to DC converters where operated from a station battery system.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may include a battery and charger circuitry to continue operation in event of AC power failure for critical applications where a station battery is not available.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Most RTUs have a section called *input status cards* to read ON/OFF information from the field.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] They do this by checking if a contact (like a switch) is open or closed at the RTU location.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Some RTUs can also count events (like how many times a contact opens/closes), but this is optional.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can monitor analog inputs of different types including 0-1 mA, 4–20 mA current loop, 0–10 V., ±2.5 V, ±5.0 V etc.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Many RTU inputs buffer larger quantities via transducers to convert and isolate real-world quantities from sensitive RTU input levels.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU can also receive analog data via a communication system from a master or intelligent electronic device (IED) sending data values to it.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] The RTU or host system translates and scales this raw data into the appropriate units such as the quantity of water left, temperature degrees, or Megawatts, before presenting the data to the user via the human–machine interface.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] RTUs may drive high current capacity relays to a digital output (or "DO") board to switch power on and off to devices in the field.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] The DO board switches voltage to the coil in the relay, which closes the high current contacts, which completes the power circuit to the device.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] RTU outputs may also consist of driving a sensitive logic input on an electronic PLC, or other electronic device using a sensitive 5 V input.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] While not as commonly used, analog outputs may be included to control devices that require varying quantities, such as graphic recording instruments (strip charts).
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Summed or processed data quantities may be generated in a master SCADA system and output for display locally or remotely, wherever needed.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Modern RTUs are usually capable of executing simple programs autonomously without involving the host computers of the DCS or SCADA system to simplify deployment and to provide redundancy for safety reasons.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU in a modern water management system will typically have code to modify its behavior when physical override switches on the RTU are toggled during maintenance-by-maintenance personnel.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] This is done for safety reasons; a miscommunication between the system operators and the maintenance personnel could cause system operators to mistakenly enable power to a water pump when it is being replaced, for example.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Maintenance personnel should have any equipment they are working on disconnected from power and locked to prevent damage and/or injury.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may be interfaced to multiple master stations and IEDs with different communication protocols (usually serial (RS-232, RS-485, RS-422) or Ethernet).
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] An RTU may support standard protocols (Modbus, IEC 60870-5-101/103/104, DNP3, IEC 60870-6-ICCP, IEC 61850 etc.) to interface any third-party software.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Data transfer may be initiated from either end using various techniques to ensure synchronization with minimal data traffic.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] The master may poll its subordinate unit (Master to RTU or RTU to IED) for changes of data on a periodic basis.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Analog value changes will usually be reported only on changes outside a set limit from the last transmitted value.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Digital (status) values observe a similar technique and only transmit groups (bytes) when one included point (bit) changes.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Another method used is where a subordinate unit initiates an update of data upon a predetermined change in analog or digital data.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Complete data transmission must be performed periodically, with either method, to ensure full synchronization and eliminate stale data.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Most communication protocols support both methods, programmable by the installer.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Multiple RTUs or IEDs may share a communications line, in a multi-drop scheme, as units are addressed uniquely and only respond to their own polls and commands.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] IED communications transfer data between the RTU and an IED.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] This can eliminate the need for many hardware status inputs, analog inputs, and relay outputs in the RTU.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Communications are accomplished by copper or fibre optics lines.
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Master communications usually occur between an RTU and a larger control system or a data collection system (incorporated into a larger system).
[src:substation-automation/remote-terminal-unit] Data may be moved using a copper, fibre optic or radio frequency communication system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:substation-automation/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:substation-automation/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:substation-automation/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:substation-automation/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:substation-automation/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:substation-automation/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:substation-automation/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:substation-automation/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:substation-automation/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:substation-automation/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:substation-automation/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:substation-automation/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:substation-automation/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:substation-automation/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:substation-automation/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:substation-automation/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:substation-automation/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:substation-automation/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:substation-automation/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:substation-automation/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:substation-automation/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:substation-automation/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:substation-automation/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:substation-automation/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:substation-automation/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:substation-automation/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:substation-automation/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:substation-automation/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:substation-automation/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:substation-automation/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:substation-automation/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:substation-automation/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:substation-automation/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:substation-automation/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:substation-automation/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:substation-automation/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:substation-automation/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:substation-automation/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
